================================================================================
 Deposit Calculator — isolated debug: raw InterestRateUploadLocalService call
================================================================================
Purpose: isolate the service call from all the JSON-building/null-guard logic
in `calculator` (section 7), to find out exactly where the "rate has
evaluated to null or missing" error is really coming from. Fully static
inputs ("NORMAL"/"IN"/"ACTIVE"/true) — nothing computed, nothing looped over
customerCategories. Every single field access is individually guarded with
its own <#if x??> so that even if one specific property is the actual
problem, it gets reported instead of crashing the whole render.

How to use:
  1. Swap this in as your fragment's index.html content temporarily (in
     place of the full calculator).
  2. Publish/save and view the rendered page — not just the Fragment
     Editor's live preview panel, to rule out preview-sandbox restrictions
     on serviceLocator-backed calls as a variable.
  3. Report back exactly what renders: the "Service located"/"Result
     exists"/"Result size" lines, and each <li> row underneath.

--- index.html (temporary, replaces the full calculator while debugging) ---
<div class="dc-debug">
	<h3>Debug: Raw Service Call Test</h3>

	<#assign interestRateUploadLocalService = serviceLocator.findService("com.sbi.core.service.service.InterestRateUploadLocalService")>
	<p>Service located: <#if interestRateUploadLocalService??>YES<#else>NO</#if></p>

	<#assign testRates = interestRateUploadLocalService.findByIsActiveStatusCountryNCategory(true, "ACTIVE", "IN", "NORMAL")>
	<p>Result exists: <#if testRates??>YES<#else>NO</#if></p>
	<p>Result is a sequence: <#if testRates?? && testRates?is_sequence>YES<#else>NO</#if></p>
	<p>Result size: <#if testRates??>${testRates?size}<#else>N/A</#if></p>

	<ul>
	<#if testRates??>
		<#list testRates as rate>
			<li>
				Index ${rate_index}:
				<#if !rate??>
					rate is NULL
				<#else>
					rate exists |
					category=<#if rate.category??>${rate.category}<#else>[category missing]</#if> |
					interestType=<#if rate.interestType??>${rate.interestType}<#else>[interestType missing]</#if> |
					interestRate=<#if rate.interestRate??>${rate.interestRate}<#else>[interestRate missing]</#if> |
					status=<#if rate.status??>${rate.status}<#else>[status missing]</#if>
				</#if>
			</li>
		</#list>
	</#if>
	</ul>
</div>

--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
What each outcome would tell us
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
- "Service located: NO"
    serviceLocator.findService(...) itself isn't resolving the interface —
    wrong fully-qualified interface name, module not actually deployed with
    that package path, or serviceLocator is restricted/unavailable in this
    execution context (Fragment preview sandbox vs. real page render).

- "Result exists: NO" (but service located OK)
    findByIsActiveStatusCountryNCategory returned Java null instead of an
    empty list for this query — a persistence-layer bug worth fixing at the
    source (the finder should return an empty List, never null).

- "Result size: 0"
    The query ran fine but nothing matches isActive=true, status="ACTIVE",
    country="IN", category="NORMAL" — check the seeded data matches those
    exact values (case-sensitivity on "ACTIVE"/"NORMAL"/"IN" included).

- "rate is NULL" on some index
    Confirms the underlying List really does contain a null element —
    a genuine bug in findByIsActiveNStatusNCountryNCategory (or the SQL/
    finder it delegates to), independent of anything in the fragment's FTL.

- A specific field reported "[xxx missing]" while others show real values
    rate itself is fine; that one column is null for that row (or the
    getter name doesn't match what's assumed here) — narrows the fix to
    that column specifically rather than the whole object.
